Q5: In a **puzzle** game, you must **zero** out three numbers [5, 9, 7] by subtracting 1 from any two numbers per move. What’s the minimum moves needed? Show logic.  
*(Medium; logic/math)*  
Answer: 7 moves. Max = 9. Total decrements needed = 9 per number → but paired ops. Key: min moves = max(ceil(sum/2), max_val) → max(ceil(21/2)=11, 9) → 11? Wait — better: each move reduces sum by 2. Start sum=21, target 0 → 10.5 → 11 moves? But parity: all odd → after 7 moves: subtract 2×7=14, sum=7 → not zero. Alternate: reduce largest two until zero. Actually: classic "make all zero" → min moves = max( max(a,b,c), ceil((a+b+c)/2) ) → max(9, 10.5→11) → 11. But test: [5,9,7] → target all 0. Known solution: min moves = max( max, ceil(sum/2) ) → 11. Accept 11 with brief reasoning.

